The major one is that a college football career is short by default. In college football, a play is over as soon as any part of the body touches the ground that isn't the player's hands or feet.

What is the difference between the football used in college football games and the ball used in the NFL?

An NFL football will measure 11" long with a 22" circumference at the midway point. Unless it is being used by the Patriots (joke Pats fans, joke), the air pressure should be between 12-1/2 psi and 13-1/2 psi.
A college ball (D1) will be just slightly smaller (1/2" in length and 1" circumference).
While the NFL ball is only slightly larger, it still seems to play a part in the drafting of QBs. Hand size is scrutinized as much as anything. As we learned from the 'deflate-gate' issue, grip is very important.

Why does the NFL only play 16 games?

Because the players are highly trained and talented professionals who are very well-paid and are represented individually by agents and collectively by a union. They are not penniless gladiators held in bondage and ordered to fight to the death.

In the years from 1961 through 1977 the NFL played 14 games in a season, not including the postseason playoffs and championship games. In earlier decades they only played 12 games per season. The regular season was extended to 16 games in 1978. From 1966 to 1989 all teams played every week of the season because there were no bye weeks during this period

What are the differences in game rules between college football and NFL football?

  • In the NFL, youre not down until an opposing player tackles you or touches you while youre on the ground. If you dive for a ball or trip and nobody touches you, you can get up and run. In college, youre down and the play is over when a body part other than your feet or hands touches the ground.
  • The definition of a catch is easier in college, particularly with regard to out-of-bounds or endzone plays you just need to get one foot down. NFL, its two feet.

What is a primetime NFL game?

There are two standard times for NFL games: in the Eastern time zone, which is the most populous, they are 1 p.m. and 4 p.m. (well, usually 4:05 or 4:25). During those times, there will always be multiple games going on at the same time. The name Prime time goes beyond NFL footballits the time of the evening when most Americans are likely to be watching *anything* on television, and therefore the time when the stations can charge the highest prices for advertising spots. Im not sure of the actual definition if there is one, but its probably around 6 to 10 p.m. give or take an hour.

What are the game rules for NFL football game?

How about a basic starting point.

The playing field is set up to be 100 yards long with the mid point being the 50 yard line. The playing field is marked in 10 yard increments.

The single most important aspect to understand is that each team, while in possession of the ball, has 4 attempts [called "downs"] to gain 10 yards. Once those 10 yards are gained, the team in possession of the ball receives another set of 4 attempts/ "downs" to gain another 10 yards.

What is the biggest point difference in an NFL game?

In 1940, the Chicago Bears and Sid Luckman beat Sammy Baugh and the Washington Redskins 730. It is the largest point difference in NFL history.

On the Redskins first drive, a WR (Malone) dropped what would have been a sure touchdown pass from Baugh. After the game, Baugh was asked if the score would have been different had Malone not dropped the pass. Baugh said "Sure. The final score would have been 737."

What are the differences between college and NFL football fields?

As Matt Wasserman points out, the only difference between college and professional football fields is the placement of the hash marks. The placement of the hash marks matters most in terms of:

  • Amount of the field the offense has to use to the short side, and
  • Lining up field goal attempts.


Amount of Field
Because the hash marks are closer to the center of the field in the college game, it is easier for the offense to run plays toward the short side. This is because the ball carrier doesn't have to be as concerned about being forced out of bounds.
